arch:property.oc:show_val: This unit is described as a midden-filled (or possibly midden) pit into mudbricky fill. The dry-sieved portion is a medium-sized sample of primarily sheep-sized and caprine material, with some other species including mustelid, canid, Bos, and Sus. There are four worked bone fragments in this sample (F. 1, 2, 3, 4). None of them join with each other, although three of them seem to be from similar points. Sheep-sized material includes long bone shaft fragments, ribs, vertebrae, and skull fragments. There are more rib fragments than in many units; the long bone shaft fragments still outnumber them, but by perhaps only 5:3. There is a small amount of pig-sized material, mostly long bone shaft fragments with a few skull and rib fragments, and a small amount of cow-sized material, mostly long bone shaft fragments with a few skull fragments, two rib fragments, and one scapular fragment. There are also a few hare-sized long bone shaft fragments. Most diagnostics are caprine, but there are a few other species represented. Caprine material comes from all of the regions of the body, but there are far more meaty limb bone fragments than feet and teeth. Many of the caprine fragments are from young individuals. All other taxa (mustelid, canid, Bos, Sus) are represented by a few fragments from throughout the body, not enough to discuss body part representation. However, there are some indications that the cow-sized material was more highly processed: there are relatively few Bos diagnostics, and no equid diagnostics, and the cow-sized long bones are fragmented with mostly old break ends. The articular surfaces are missing from the sample. This midden may be slightly less diverse than other midden samples, as there are few non-caprine fragments, but this may also be because it is a small sample for a midden. The modal fragment size in this sample is fairly small for a midden, around 5 or 6 cm. The largest fragments are 11 cm. About 10% of the sample is burnt, mostly at low temperatures, but about 10% of the burnt material is calcined. Most of the burnt material is long bones (30% of which are burnt) and ribs, with only a few burnt feet or skull fragments. There is little gnawed bone (ca. 1%) and even less digested bone (ca. 0.5%). There are also a few fragments of trampled bone (ca. 1%), probably background noise. The sample is in mixed good condition, generally surface condition three with a little four. Although the sample is in generally good condition, indicating fairly swift deposition, the sample appears to have multiple origins. The fragments have had different taphonomic histories, including different kinds of burning and some carnivore effects. The sample appears to be several different (subsequent?) depositions of food waste. There is an articulating set of lumbar vertebrae, indicating that this is not an entirely mixed sample and that some fragments went into the ground together. NR 2008: Sample 2 (by inference; tag does not have number) >4mm flotation 100% sorted, recorded as diagnostics and flot frags only. It is a largish sample that differs most strikingly from the dry-sieved material in that it is mostly burnt. I think virtually all the pieces are at least slightly burnt, the majority are quite burnt or carbonized, and a few are calcined. It looks like burning in a reducing atmosphere, i.e., after burial. So the flot sample must have caught an area of in situ burning. Otherwise it seems reasonably similar to the rest of the unit. It is heavily sheep-size with some large mammal. Diagnostics, of which there are quite a few, are mostly sheep/goat with a bit of cattle (although no IDs as such), equid, and fox. Body part distribution is fairly even. Surface condition seems generally fairly fresh, and there are delicate pieces such as costal cartilage. The burning and flotation tank have led to many modern breaks, but originally the fragmentation seems to have been moderate. There is some digestion. This part looks like midden that was subsequently burnt by a fire above.
